THE BURNSIDE CARBINE WAS ONE OF THE "BIG 3" CARBINES USED DURING THE CIVIL WAR. 

5TH MODEL, WHICH MOST COLLECTORS USED TO CALL THE 4TH MODEL, IS SERIAL NUMBERED 19182, ON BOTH THE TOP OF THE RECEIVER AND THE BREECH BLOCK. 

43,940 CARBINES WERE ISSUED TO BOTH UNION AND CONFEDERATE UNITS. ACTUALLY MADE IN 1863, BUT PAT 1864. AN ORIGINAL CIVIL WAR ISSUED 1864 MODEL BURNSIDE CARBINE 5TH MODEL. SINGLE-SHOT, BREECH-LOADING WEAPON THAT USED A TAPERED OR CONE-SHAPED BRASS CARTRIDGE. MODERN COMPON-ENTS FOR MAKING AMMUNITION ARE AVAILABLE FROM SEVERAL SOURCES. ACTUALLY ISSUED IN 1863, THE CARBINES CARRY AN 1864 DATE STAMP ENDING WITH FINAL ORDERS WHICH WERE SENT TO THE GOVERNMENT IN AUGUST, 1864. BURNSIDE BEGAN MAKING SPENCER RIFLES FOR THE ARMY THEREAFTER.

title: For Sale:  Colt Government Model - Jim CLark Custom Meltdown From 2000 - Unfired
postcontent:
This is a Colt Government Model that has had the Meltdown conversion done in early 2000 from Clark Custom Guns in Princeton, Louisiana. It was shipped to have the conversion done the very month that Jim Clark, Sr. passed away. If you're familiar with Jim Clark's fame both as a National Bullseye Champion shooter as well as the first President of the American Pistolsmith's Guild, then you already know what the famous meltdown package is about. But if not, what follows is the complete work included in this package.

From the work order:
Adjust extractor tension		King Palm Swell GS		Accuracy package
Big bushing & reverse plug		Lower ejection port		Cocobolo smooth grips
Combat hammer				Meltdown dehorn		Hex head grip screws
Extra power mag spring		Rear sight-Clark		        Grip screw bushing
Front sight-long			        Throat & polish
Function Test wHP ammo		Trigger job
King extended thumb safety

Included is the original Colt box and all papers, tool, original Colt grips, etc. as well as all the paperwork from Clark Custom Guns (including the test target initialed by the pistolsmith and the list of ammunition used for the test.) I put this pistol in the safe and have never fired it since the conversion. I am old now and am simply never going to take this gun to the range. It's a beautifully understated piece, in my opinion, and I've never seen another with the deep matte blue this one has. And how to say this in the nicest possible way: I'll be using the funds from this sale to enhance my granddaughter's college account, so please don't waste my time and yours with lowball offers or trades. Thanks, but I'm not interested. If you're looking at Armslist from outside Colorado, yes, I will ship this gun from my dealer to yours for $30. If your in the Denver metro area, I will pay for the BGC fees at Gander Mountain in Thornton. I also have links to nine large photos (1024) or can send them to you vial email. Thanks for looking.
